In Christian thought, and much of European metaphysics, the ego is the figure of mortality (as opposed to the human-animal distinction that is Epicurus about which there is a distinction between instinct and instinct, both essential for human development). This is a commentary on the necessity in human affairs of class or caste; and, a claim about the will to power as a fundamental description of life. The notion of the beast of prey or the infamous image of the ‘blond beast’ belongs here. Notice in these passages that the beast of prey image is by no means always a positive one: on what and how it preys, and with what good conscience, is the difference. While culture and the state begin with the ‘blond beast’, the further development of the human type will occur through ‘bad conscience’ – a phenomenon utterly impossible for that beast.

