 it is 'a miracle'. The free spirit and ‘seeker after knowledge’ must be able to see with many eyes, to see with many senses. Such clarity, judgement, and clarity of purpose leads to the idea of the pathos of distance, because thus far the Greeks were not scale-like, but reached to a higher nobility. This is implicitly acknowledged that the ‘complete and authentic antagonism’ is between Homer and Plato: the former the deifier of life, the latter its ‘slanderer’.

